ut 1222","1222":"1222","1200":"1200","1253":"1253","Abt 1226":"about 1226","1282":"1282","Abt 1228":"about 1228","Smallburgh, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Smallburgh, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom",", Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from any of the places called Ingham, particularly in Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Suffolk. The placename is from the Old English personal name <i>Inga</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. In Yorkshire this name was sometimes confused with   Bingham   in the 18th century.","English (of Norman origin): variant of the obsolete Norman surname <i>Engaine</i>; see   Gain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bingham","meanings":["English (Dorset) and Irish (County Mayo): habitational name from Bingham (Nottinghamshire). The placename is probably from an Old English folk-name <i>Bynningas</i> (‘the people associated with a man named <i>Bynna</i>’), or possibly from an unattested Old English word <i>bing</i> ‘a kettle-shaped hollow’, + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Irish (Ulster, of Scottish origin): altered form of   Bigham  .","American shortened and altered form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames such as   Bingenheimer  ."]},{"name":"Gain","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for a cunning person, from <i>Engaine</i>, which is based on Old French <i>engaigne</i> ‘ingenuity, cunning, trickery’.","English: habitiational name from any of various places called after the <i>Engain</i> family, including Colne Engaine and Gaynes Park (Essex), d'Engaine's Farm (Cambridgeshire), and Aston Ingham (Hereford). <i>Engaine</i> (see 1 above) was the name of a powerful Norman family with lands in several counties. The original form of the surname has since died out, surviving as <i>Gain</i> and its variants. There has also been considerable confusion with   Ingham  .","French: nickname from a noun derivative of Old French <i>gaainier</i> ‘to obtain, gain, win’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Alice de Ingham was born in 1205, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 4 sons with Walter de Ingham."},"et":{"1205–":"1205–Surnud","1200–1253":"1200–1253","1213–1282":"1213–1282","1222–Mal